The police in Bauchi State have arrested suspected kidnappers who killed a 15-year-old-boy, Abubakar Sadiq Suleiman, after collecting N5.5 million ransom. The command’s spokesman, Kamal Datti, confirmed yesterday that operatives have arrested some of the suspected kidnappers believed to have killed Suleiman, a secondary school student in Bauchi. Datti said that investigations are still to arrest the remaining suspects in the gang of the kidnappers. He said: “We are disturbed by this incident and the police in Bauchi are on the trail of the remaining culprits and bring them to book.” Narrating how the teenager was killed, his father, Dr Suleiman Auwal, said: “I received a call from my son and heard some people asking me if I was his father, I confirmed to them that I was his father. “I was in the office when they called me, they informed me that they had kidnapped my son, and that I must pay a ransom of N10 million,” he told newsmen in Bauchi. Auwal said that the kidnappers called him after two days, demanding for N7 million and after a series of pleas and negotiations, the sum of N5.5 million was paid as ransom. The bereaved father said that the money was paid through two accounts, but regretted that his efforts could not save his son. “They said we should go to Inkil or Kangere, a suburb of the metropolis to pick my son; when we got there, we could not see him to pick him as promised by his abductors.” Auwal said the police had recovered his remains. LEADERSHIP recalls that the abducted elder brother to Bauchi State governor, Bala Mohammed regained freedom from kidnappers a few days ago.